The degree of operating leverage (DOL) refers to the sensitivity of the company's cashflow with regards to the change in the quantity sold. This can be solved using different formulas:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{DOL}&=1+\dfrac{\text{FC}}{\text{OCF}}\\
\text{DOL}&=\dfrac{\Delta \text{OCF}}{\Delta \text{Q}}
\end{aligned}$$

To solve this problem, we will focus on the second formula.

When we talk about the $\Delta \text{OCF}$ and $\Delta \text{Q}$, we refer to these in terms of percentage change. Therefore, we can rewrite the formula as:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{DOL}&=\dfrac{\frac{\text{OCF}_{\text{new}}-\text{OCF}_{\text{old}}}{\text{OCF}_{\text{old}}}}{\frac{\text{Q}_{\text{new}}-\text{Q}_{\text{old}}}{\text{Q}_{\text{old}}}}
\end{aligned}$$

Take note that in the computation for the old and new OCF, only the quantity changes. So, if we substitute the formula of OCF to the formula for DOL in Step 2, we will get:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{DOL}&=\dfrac{\frac{(\text{P}-\text{v})\times(1-\text{T})+(\text{T}\times \text{D})\times(\text{Q}_\text{new}-\text{Q}_{\text{old}})+\text{FC}\times(1-\text{T})}{\text{OCF}_{\text{old}}}}{\frac{\text{Q}_{\text{new}}-\text{Q}_{\text{old}}}{\text{Q}_{\text{old}}}}
\end{aligned}$$

Rearranging and combining the terms will give us:
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{DO}L&=\dfrac{(\text{P}-\text{v})\times(1-\text{T})+(\text{T}\times \text{D})\times(\text{Q}_\text{new}-\text{Q}_{\text{old}})+\text{FC}\times(1-\text{T})}{\text{OCF}_{\text{old}}} \times \dfrac{\text{Q}_{\text{old}}}{\text{Q}_{\text{new}}-\text{Q}_{\text{old}}}\\[15 pt]

&=\dfrac{\text{OCF}_{\text{old}}-(\text{T} \times \text{D})+\text{FC}\times(1-\text{T})}{\text{OCF}_{\text{old}}}
\end{aligned}$$
